input: In article <1r6g8fINNe88@ceti.cs.unc.edu>, jge@cs.unc.edu (John Eyles) writes: > A friend has what is apparently a fairly minor case of Crohn > disease.
> But she can not seem to eat certain foods, such as fresh vegetables, > without discomfort, and of course she wants to avoid a recurrence.
> Her question is: are there any nutritionists who specialize in the > problems of people with Crohn disease ?
> (I saw the suggestion of lipoxygnase inhibitors like tea and turmeric).
> Thanks in advance, > John Eyles All your friend really has to do is find a Registered Dietician(RD).
While  most work in hospitals and clinics, many major cities will have RD who  are in "private practice" so to speak.
Many physicans will refer their  patients with Crohn disease to RD for dietary help.
If you can get  your friend physician to make a referral, medical insurance should pay for  the RD services just like the services of a physical therapist.

The  better medical insurance plans will cover this but even if your friend  plan does not, it would be well worth the cost to get on a good diet to  control the intestinal discomfort and help the intestinal lining heal.

Crohn disease is an inflammatory disease of the intestinal lining and  lipoxygenase inhibitors may help by decreasing leukotriene formation but  I am not aware of tea or turmeric containing lipoxygenase inhibitors.
For  bad inflammation, steroids are used but for a mild case, the side effects  are not worth the small benefit gained by steroid use.
Upjohn is developing  a new lipoxygenase inhibitor that should greatly help deal with  inflammatory diseases but it is not available yet.
